{"title": "Animal Metaphor", "content": "Sometimes an animal (or two animals) can symbolize a character or characters (humans or anthropomorphized animals) in a work. If the characters are human, these animals will generally be their pets, but in works of fantasy it's not uncommon for the characters to be transformed into animals and have to work together to return to safety and human form, learning more about each other along the way.\n\nThe most common form of this trope is the portrayal of two animals whose relationship mirrors or symbolizes the relationship between their owners.\n\nCan be case of Truth in Television in that pets' behaviour tends to reflect their masters' moods.\n\nRelated to What Do You Mean, It's Not Symbolic?. Subtrope of Animal Motifs. Supertrope to Caged Bird Metaphor.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AnimalMetaphor", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/LightNovel/Toradora", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Bleach", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/ZatchBell", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Anime/Pokemon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/KodomoNoOmocha", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/WesternAnimation/TheMagicSchoolBus", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/TheUltimateSora", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/TheLionKingIISimbasPride", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Disney/Pocahontas", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/DefinitelyMaybe", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheWindAndTheLion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/JamesBond", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Skyfall", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/Spectre", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/FromRussiaWithLove", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/HarryPotterAndThePrisonerOfAzkaban", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/HarryPotterAndTheHalfBloodPrince", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/EnidBlyton", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/SherlockHolmes", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/TamoraPierce", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/CircleOfMagic", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/ErastFandorin", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/TheStateCounsellor", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Literature/BelisariusSeries", "/pmwiki/pmwik